article.description:
Keith Waleskowski scored 16 points and Sean
Finn added 15 as No. 22 Dayton showed little sign of rust after a
12-day layoff in defeating Rhode Island 74-57 Thursday night in the
second round of the Atlantic 10 Tournament.
article.headline: Dayton to face St. Joseph's in semifinals
article.linkText: Dayton bounces Rhode Island out of A-10 tourney again
article.story: DAYTON, Ohio (AP) -- A 12-day layoff didn't hurt Dayton. In fact, the Flyers (No. 21 ESPN/USA Today, No. 22 AP) looked remarkably fresh in beating Rhode Island 74-57 Thursday night in the quarterfinals of the Atlantic 10 tournament. Dayton used its big men to dominate the Rams, getting 16 points from 6-foot-9 forward Keith Waleskowski and 15 points from 6-foot-11 center Sean Finn. "We weren't rusty,'' Finn said. "We stayed in the same flow we've been in the past few months.'' Dayton had not played since March 1 because St. Bonaventure forfeited its last two games, including Saturday's game against Dayton. The Bonnies were stripped of six wins and barred from the tournament for using center Jamil Terrell, who failed to meet NCAA junior college transfer guidelines. Waleskowski said Dayton couldn't wait to play a game after such a long layoff. The Flyers had been forced to settle for practices and scrimmages for the nearly two-week layoff. "We were all excited just to get going again,'' Waleskowski said. "It had been so long since we were in a game.'' Dayton (22-5) advances to the semifinals Friday to play St. Joseph's, which defeated La Salle 68-48 in an earlier game. It was the third straight season that the Flyers knocked Rhode Island out of the conference tournament. The Flyers used the height advantage of their post men, pounding the ball underneath to Finn and Waleskowski. Dayton had 40 points in the paint and 18 second-chance points. Rhode Island (18-11) played a zone defense for much of the game to try to cut off Dayton's passes to the inside and force the Flyers to shoot from the perimeter. But Dayton shot well from the outside, and four Flyers finished in double figures. "They got the ball inside and also shot well from the perimeter,'' Rhode Island coach Jim Baron said. "They're a very good team, and they could be dangerous down the road.'' In the first half, the Rams went for more than 10 minutes without scoring a field goal, shooting just 21 percent. Dayton went on a 16-0 run to take an 25-10 lead at 8:30, and at halftime the Flyers led 39-16. It was the Flyers' biggest halftime lead of the season and the fewest points scored against Dayton in the first half. "Overall, I thought it was one of our best halves of the season,'' Dayton coach Oliver Purnell said. "Our inside guys were tremendous. Sean got us started, Nate (Green) was big in the middle and Keith sort of carried us down the stretch.'' Rhode Island staged a comeback in the second half, hitting 11 of their first 12 shots, including all six of their 3-point attempts. The Rams had cut Dayton's lead to nine with 12:26 left before missing their next seven shots. Brooks Hall and D.J. Stelly hit 3-pointers to put Dayton back in control. "It was a great comeback, but we just got too far behind early,'' Baron said. "We made a run and closed to within nine, but they kept being productive and getting good shots.'' Sophomore guard Dustin Hellenga had 18 points for Rhode Island, including four 3-pointers. Dayton's victory snapped Rhode Island's three-game winning streak. Dayton is 15-1 on their home court this season, losing only to Xavier.
